        {
            'question_text': 'During a morbidity and mortality meeting, the definition of medical error is discussed. Which of the following correctly defines a medical error in the ED, and how does it differ from a standard clinical complication?',
            'options': [
                'A) Medical error is when a patient does not like their hospital food; a complication is a missed diagnostic test.',
                "B) Medical error is when a patient deteriorates from a missed/delayed diagnosis, or has an unexpected complication because something wasn't diagnosed; a complication is sustained from the anticipated course of a known illness.",
                'C) Medical error is any complication that occurs after 240 minutes; a complication is any event that occurs within a minute of arrival.',
                'D) Medical error is a failure of the electronic medical record; a complication is a failure of the triage nurse to assign Category 1.',
                'E) Medical error is when a patient requires aeromedical transfer; a complication is when they are discharged home.',
            ],
            'correct_answer_letter': 'B',
            'explanation': "Option analysis:\nOption A: Incorrect - Food quality is not a medical error.\nOption B: Correct - Medical error is defined as deterioration from a missed or delayed diagnosis, or an unexpected complication because something wasn't diagnosed first. A clinical complication is sustained as an anticipated course of their known illness.\nOption C: Incorrect - Time limits do not define medical errors vs. complications.\nOption D: Incorrect - EMR failures are technical issues, and triage categorization is an urgency assessment, not the definition of medical error.\nOption E: Incorrect - Transfer and discharge are disposition pathways, not errors.\n\nClinical reasoning: Understanding this distinction is crucial for medical quality improvement. A complication from a known disease process is a recognized risk, whereas a deterioration from a missed diagnosis represents a preventable failure.",
            'key_learning_points': 'Medical error involves preventable missed/delayed diagnoses leading to deterioration. Standard complications are the anticipated course of a known disease.',
            'image_url': '',
        },
        {
            'question_text': 'An intern is reviewing the case of "Doctor A" who managed a Category 4 patient presenting with a wrist laceration. Which of the following correctly describes Doctor A\'s clinical errors and cognitive biases?',
            'options': [
                'A) Doctor A used an arm board and gloves, but forgot to document the procedure.',
                'B) Doctor A suffered from anchoring bias, assumed a Category 4 was minor, cherry-picked the patient for speed, performed a quick clean/suture in a chair, and missed a deep tendon sheath laceration.',
                'C) Doctor A consulted the Orthopedic team too early, causing a delay in suturing the wound.',
                'D) Doctor A spent too much time exploring the wound under good lighting, causing the patient to miss their bus.',
                'E) Doctor A assumed the patient was a neonate and initiated a full sepsis workup.',
            ],
            'correct_answer_letter': 'B',
            'explanation': 'Option analysis:\nOption A: Incorrect - Doctor A did not use an arm board or properly explore the wound.\nOption B: Correct - Doctor A was busy/hungry, cherry-picked the case, performed a quick clean/suture in a chair, suffered from anchoring bias (assuming Cat 4 meant a minor issue), and missed a tendon sheath laceration.\nOption C: Incorrect - Doctor A did not consult Orthopedics.\nOption D: Incorrect - Doctor A did not explore the wound or use good lighting.\nOption E: Incorrect - The patient was not a neonate, and no sepsis workup was indicated.\n\nClinical reasoning: Doctor A fell victim to "anchoring bias," conflating a low triage urgency category with a low-complexity pathology. This cognitive shortcut led to a superficial assessment and a missed deep structural injury.',
            'key_learning_points': 'Conflating low triage urgency with low pathological complexity leads to anchoring bias and missed structural injuries.',
            'image_url': '',
        },
