        {
            'question_text': 'You are preparing to hand over a patient to the night team. According to the SBAR/ISBAR handover framework, which of the following correctly describes the four components of this communication tool?',
            'options': [
                'A) Situation: Patient demographics, food allergies, and transport method; Background: Family medical history; Assessment: Social work review; Recommendation: Dietary plan.',
                'B) Situation: Patient identifier (name/age/sex), presenting reason, working diagnosis, and significant management (e.g., fluid boluses for shock); Background: Pertinent medical/surgical/social history; Assessment: Current clinical condition (e.g., stable, or ventilator settings), pain score/management; Recommendation: Clear list of outstanding tasks to be chased/monitored.',
                'C) Situation: Triage category and wait time; Background: Year the hospital was built; Assessment: General medical condition; Recommendation: Estimated discharge time.',
                'D) Situation: Method of arrival; Background: Standard general practice medical records; Assessment: Nursing care plan; Recommendation: Inpatient ward bed booking.',
                'E) Situation: Clinician name and shift time; Background: Previous ED admissions; Assessment: Full system CT scan results; Recommendation: Surgical consent.',
            ],
            'correct_answer_letter': 'B',
            'explanation': 'Option analysis:\nOption A: Incorrect - These do not represent the clinical components of the SBAR handover tool.\nOption B: Correct - SBAR stands for: Situation (demographics, presenting reason, diagnosis, key management like fluids for shock), Background (pertinent medical/surgical/social history), Assessment (clinical state, pain score/management), and Recommendation (tasks to be done/chased).\nOption C: Incorrect - Hospital build date is irrelevant, and wait times are not core Situation elements.\nOption D: Incorrect - General practice records are too broad for a focused Background handover.\nOption E: Incorrect - Clinician shift times are not the Situation, and a full-system CT is not standard for all Assessments.\n\nClinical reasoning: SBAR structures communication to prevent information loss during handovers. It ensures the incoming clinician understands the acute situation, historical context, current physiological state, and the direct tasks they must perform.',
            'key_learning_points': 'SBAR stands for Situation, Background, Assessment, and Recommendation, organizing critical clinical details to ensure a safe transition of care.',
            'image_url': '',
        },
        {
            'question_text': 'The emergency department is experiencing severe crowding due to "access block." Which of the following correctly defines access block and describes its impact on clinical safety and the NEAT target?',
            'options': [
                'A) Access block is when patients cannot physically enter the hospital front door due to weather; it has no impact on patient safety.',
                'B) Access block is when admitted patients must remain in the ED because there are no available inpatient beds; it restricts ED capacity for new patients, leads to poorer outcomes, and violates the NEAT 4-hour target.',
                'C) Access block is when the helicopter cannot land due to high winds; it primarily affects Category 5 patients.',
                'D) Access block is when junior doctors fail to complete their clinical documentation; it is managed by the triage nurse.',
                'E) Access block is when the hospital avoidance program (HITH) is full; it only affects neonatal patients.',
            ],
            'correct_answer_letter': 'B',
            'explanation': 'Option analysis:\nOption A: Incorrect - Access block is a systemic bed-availability issue, not a weather block.\nOption B: Correct - Access block is when admitted patients remain in the ED because there are no inpatient beds. It restricts new patient capacity, is associated with poorer outcomes, and directly impacts the NEAT (National Emergency Access Target) 4-hour rule.\nOption C: Incorrect - Aeromedical landing failures are weather/operational issues, not access block.\nOption D: Incorrect - Access block is a hospital-wide bed capacity issue, not a documentation failure.\nOption E: Incorrect - Access block affects patients of all ages and is a whole-of-hospital problem.\n\nClinical reasoning: Access block is a major driver of ED crowding. It traps resources (beds and nurses) on admitted patients, preventing the department from assessing and treating new, undifferentiated high-acuity presentations.',
            'key_learning_points': 'Access block is the inability to transfer admitted patients to inpatient beds, resulting in ED crowding, poorer patient outcomes, and failure to meet the 4-hour NEAT target.',
            'image_url': '',
        },
