        {
            'question_text': "A 28-year-old male is brought to the resuscitation bay after ingesting an estimated forty 25 mg amitriptyline tablets. On arrival, he is hypotensive, drowsy, and his 12-lead ECG reveals a QRS width of 165 ms. What is the mechanism of action of the antidote required to manage this patient's cardiac toxicity? ( )",
            'options': [
                'A) Competitive antagonism at the GABA-A receptor to prevent seizures',
                'B) Intravenous sodium bicarbonate; acts as a competitive antagonist at fast sodium channels, and the resulting alkalemia is cardioprotective',
                'C) Chemical neutralization of the tricyclic antidepressant molecules in the systemic circulation',
                'D) Reactivation of the myocardial sodium-potassium ATPase pump',
                'E) Forced renal excretion of the drug via urinary acidification',
            ],
            'correct_answer_letter': 'B',
            'explanation': 'Tricyclic antidepressants block myocardial fast sodium channels, causing QRS widening and life-threatening ventricular arrhythmias. Intravenous sodium bicarbonate is the antidote. It provides a sodium load to overcome the channel blockade and induces alkalemia, which decreases drug binding to the sodium channel.\n\nOption analysis:\nOption A: Incorrect. This describes flumazenil, which is contraindicated in TCA overdoses as it can precipitate severe seizures.\nOption B: Correct. Sodium bicarbonate is the antidote. It acts as a competitive antagonist at fast sodium channels (by raising extracellular sodium), and the resulting alkalemia (target pH 7.45-7.55) is cardioprotective.\nOption C: Incorrect. Bicarbonate does not bind or chemically neutralize amitriptyline.\nOption D: Incorrect. Bicarbonate does not reactivate the Na+/K+ ATPase pump.\nOption E: Incorrect. Acidifying the urine is dangerous and does not enhance TCA clearance.\n\nClinical reasoning: A QRS >160 ms puts the patient at extreme risk of ventricular arrhythmias. Prompt administration of sodium bicarbonate narrow the QRS complex and prevents cardiac arrest.',
            'key_learning_points': 'Sodium bicarbonate is the antidote for TCA-induced cardiotoxicity (QRS widening). It works via competitive sodium channel blockade reversal and cardioprotective alkalemia.',
            'image_url': '',
        },
