        {
            'question_text': 'You have just inserted a nasogastric tube in an awake patient on the ward. Which of the following is the gold standard method to verify the correct placement of the tube before administering any medication or fluids?',
            'options': [
                'A) Injecting 20 mL of air and listening for a gurgle over the epigastrium.',
                'B) Testing aspirated fluid with litmus paper to confirm acidity.',
                'C) Obtaining a chest X-ray.',
                'D) Verifying the depth markings of the tube at the nose matches your measurements.',
                'E) Checking if the patient can speak clearly without coughing.',
            ],
            'correct_answer_letter': 'C',
            'explanation': 'The source notes list three ways to check placement (CXR, litmus paper, air gurgle) but state that only one is the gold standard: "chest X-ray... but don\'t ever put anything down the tube until you\'ve got that chest X-ray, even if you think it\'s in the right place. Not good enough."\n\nClinical reasoning: An NGT can accidentally sit in the bronchus or trachea, especially in patients with impaired reflexes. This can still produce a false "gurgle" or even acidic-like aspirate. A chest X-ray is the only definitive way to visualize the path of the tube into the stomach.',
            'key_learning_points': 'Chest X-ray is the gold standard method for verifying NGT placement. Never introduce any fluids, feeds, or medications down an NGT before confirming correct placement on chest X-ray. Bedside checks (litmus, air auscultation) are useful screening tools but are not definitive.',
            'image_url': '',
        },
        {
            'question_text': 'An obtunded 74-year-old stroke patient in the emergency department has an NGT inserted for decompression. The placement was not verified by X-ray, and a nurse administered 100 mL of water down the tube. The patient subsequently develops severe respiratory distress. What is the most likely pathophysiological explanation?',
            'options': [
                'A) The NGT triggered a vasovagal response from esophageal distension.',
                'B) The NGT was misplaced into the trachea, causing direct fluid delivery into the lungs (pneumonitis).',
                'C) The patient experienced a localized esophageal perforation.',
                'D) The water caused acute gastric dilatation and diaphragmatic splinting.',
                'E) The tube was coiled in the hypopharynx, causing vocal cord spasm.',
            ],
            'correct_answer_letter': 'B',
            'explanation': 'The source notes warn of the danger of not verifying placement: "if you\'ve put it into the trachea and you haven\'t realized... and then you put fluid down it... you have now caused fluid in the chest/pneumonitis... If they\'re obtunded, they\'re not going to tell you it\'s in their trachea."\n\nClinical reasoning: Obtunded patients often have silent aspiration or impaired cough reflexes, meaning they will not cough or struggle if a tube enters their airway. Infusing fluid directly into the lungs leads to severe respiratory failure (chemical pneumonitis).',
            'key_learning_points': 'Obtunded patients may not show signs of airway irritation (coughing) during tracheal NGT misplacement. Infusing fluid into an unverified NGT can cause severe chemical pneumonitis. Verifying placement with a chest X-ray is critical to patient safety.',
            'image_url': '',
        },
