        {
            'question': 'What is "debriefing to manage," and when is it indicated?',
            'answer': 'It is a debriefing format used when emotional reactions and distress are high after a traumatic event.\nIt provides low-key opportunities to acknowledge and normalize reactions, share experiences, and identify further support needs, without asking participants to explore the details of what happened. It also ensures team members have access to mental health professionals.',
        },
        {
            'question': 'What practical strategies should a facilitator employ during a "debriefing to manage" when participants are highly distressed?',
            'answer': 'Provide control by ensuring participation is entirely voluntary (participants can choose to attend all, part, or none of the session).\nBe passive, focusing on promoting peer discussion rather than teaching.\nRespect the preferences and boundaries of those involved.\nAcknowledge, normalize, and validate any expressed emotions.\nFocus on superficial cognitive processing rather than in-depth inquiry, actively avoiding re-exploring the traumatic event.\nDo not actively suppress emotional responses, but do not explore them deeply either.\nProvide immediate support, refer to mental health services as needed, and offer opportunities for future debriefing sessions in anticipation of later questions.',
        },
        {
            'question': 'What is Psychological First Aid (PFA), and when is it utilized?',
            'answer': 'PFA is utilized in the aftermath of a traumatic event when no formal debriefing is planned.\nIt is a humane, compassionate, and supportive approach aimed at addressing both practical and emotional needs.\nImportantly, it focuses on emotional needs, not emotional disclosure.',
        },
        {
            'question': 'What are the core aims of Psychological First Aid, and what is it NOT?',
            'answer': 'Its aims are to ensure safety, promote calm, promote connectedness, promote self-efficacy and group efficacy, and instill hope to help people recover naturally.\nIt is NOT: debriefing, documenting details of the trauma, treating, diagnosing, labeling, or formal counseling. It is not limited to healthcare professionals, and it is not something that everyone will need.',
        },
        {
            'question': 'What is the key clinical difference between Psychological First Aid and "debriefing to treat"?',
            'answer': 'Psychological First Aid does not encourage people to disclose or talk through their emotional responses to the trauma.',
        },
        {
            'question': 'What practical steps can be taken to successfully implement debriefing within an organization?',
            'answer': 'Establish an implementation strategy that aligns with the organization\'s culture so that debriefings are embedded within its broader scope.\nContribute to "psychological safety" (the perception that it is safe to take interpersonal risks, such as asking a seemingly basic question) by clarifying expectations.\nClarify expectations by offering explicit ground rules/goals, making the objectives of different stakeholders transparent, fostering a shared agreement, committing to confidentiality, avoiding rigid objectives, inviting input, and being inclusive.\nApply established debriefing frameworks, such as the TALK framework (Target, Analysis, Reflection, Key action), and adapt them as required.\nActively observe for signs of acute stress disorder among participants and refer them to appropriate services.\nMonitor the debriefing process to ensure it remains aligned with predefined objectives. Ask yourself: "Are you guiding a learning process, or are you beginning to treat symptoms?"\nIf participants show signs of distress or the initial request for the debriefing was vague, deliberately switch from "debriefing to learn" to "debriefing to manage."',
        },
